    <text>
        <body>
      
		<pb n="1"/>
			<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Balt.</placeName> <date>Aug 24<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1848</date></p>
			<p> Dear <addressee>Isaac</addressee></p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">Your esteemed fav. Of <date>20th</date><lb/> <add>&#63;</add> have sooner elicited a letter to <persName>Mr Hart</persName><lb/> &#40;one accompanies this&#41; has the proximity<add>&#63;</add><lb/> both from the uncertainty in which you stood as<lb/> to the more commanding claims of your own Congr&#44;<lb/> and our own as the day had not been <add>&#63;</add><lb/> fixed until <persName>Mr Jonas</persName> return. I have not been<lb/> able to name any definite day until now.</p>
			<p>We had been desirous to select the second <add>&#63;</add><lb/> for several reasons of greater convenience but<lb/> <persName>Mr J</persName> wishes to be in <placeName>N. O.</placeName> by the <date>2nd<add>&#63;</add> Oct.</date> when<lb/> his business requires his presence&#44; &#38; he has<lb/> promised to give a week to his friend in <placeName>Cini.</placeName><lb/> so we have been over<add>&#63;</add>. the <sic>rether</sic> as he informs<lb/> us you prefer the first wednesday as more<lb/> convenient to your self and <persName>Conn.</persName> you will<lb/> we hope take the occasion to spend a few days<lb/> with us&#44; we will provide you quarters either<lb/> with <persName>E. P. Cohen</persName> or <persName>Mr Bordley&#39;s</persName>&#44; as the former<lb/> has removed to a larger house&#44;&#44; I have no doubt<lb/> he <add>&#63;</add> will be happy to house you with them<lb/> let us know however if you object to either</p>
			<p>A marriage before night will be productive of<lb/> a great deal of inconvenience to us as we are<lb/> situated &#38; we have consulted <persName>Mr Rice</persName> who</p>
		<pb n="2"/>
			<p><sic>who</sic> tells us that the <add>&#63;</add> in our<lb/> laws or customs requires the ceremony at<lb/> any particular period of the day but that it<lb/> may be performed at any time &#38; that the<lb/> usage varies in different countries.</p>
			<p>We have a precedent moreover in our own<lb/> Congr. <persName>Mrs. E. P. Cohen</persName> tells us she was married<lb/> at 8 o&#39;clock in the evening.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">Please present our<lb/> warmest congratulations to our friend <persName>Carvalho</persName><lb/> we have not the satisfaction of knowing the<lb/> lady even by report&#44; but hope &#38; doubt not<lb/> she is one every way qualified to promote<lb/> his happiness. bid him recollect his<lb/> promise to come to <persName>Rosalies</persName> wedding &#38; tell<lb/> him the day. We shall however enclose<lb/> him an invitation&#59; Tell him he is designated<lb/> as groomsman&#44; let the <persName>Sticks</persName><add>&#63;</add> come by<lb/> all means.</p>
			<p>Our love to <persName>Mrs Rehine</persName> and<lb/> <persName>Mr Seixas</persName> &#38; when you write</p>
          <p rend="indent(5)">Truly yours</p>
          <p rend="indent(7)"><persName role="author">E. Block.</persName></p>
          <p rend="indent(4)">Please let us know at<lb/> once if the day suits.<lb/> your convenience<lb/> as we wish the invitations<lb/> to conform <add>&#63;</add></p>
		<pb n="3"/>
			<p>To</p>
			<p><addressee>Revd. Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
          <p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>No 118 North 4<hi rend="sup">th</hi> St</placeName></p>
          <p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName></p>
          
